<hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050318085617/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/704"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050318085617im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_704_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=731110d15abc7cd262afc5a443673436&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="ECS Computer Labs" title="ECS Computer Labs (Copyright: Grant Lynch)" border="0" width="120" height="78" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050318085617/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/704">New School scholarships to benefit undergraduates from 2006</a></h3><p>The School of Electronics and Computer Science has announced that it will be offering 25 undergraduate student scholarships of £2000 per annum each year from October 2006. Announcing the scholarship scheme, which will build to an annual commitment of £200,000, Head of School, Professor Wendy Hall, said: 'We will be working hard to ensure that we offer a study experience for all our students that matches the best in the world.'</p><p></p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050318085617/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/701"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050318085617im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_701_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=25ba4d1303cd316938b2f3134e85e6af&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Zepler Building, Highfield Campus" title="Zepler Building, Highfield Campus (Copyright: ECS)" border="0" width="90" height="120" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050318085617/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/701">Can machines learn? Find out at PASCAL Challenges Workshop</a></h3><p>A workshop being held in Southampton from 11 to 13 April will investigate the learning power of machines and report advances. The Workshop is organized by the PASCAL Network which is led by  Professor John Shawe-Taylor of the School of Electronics and Computer Science. It will present the results of four challenge projects set over the last year and report on state-of-the-art machine learning.</p></div><hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050318085617/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/700"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050318085617im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_700_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=f3fec725051f36f3b998820e19bfd7fc&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="" title="" border="0" width="76" height="120" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050318085617/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/700">ECS researcher applies knowledge management to politics</a></h3><p>Dr Kieron O'Hara, Senior Research Fellow in ECS, has written a book which will be of particular interest to the UK's political parties as a general election looms on the horizon. Dr O'Hara has taken his expertise in knowledge management for organisations and looked at how it could be applied to a government, a country, or a political party. His new book, After Blair: Conservatism Beyond Thatcher, published this month by Icon Books, embarks on a quest for an ideological answer to the Conservatives’ difficulties.</p><p></p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050318085617/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/698"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050318085617im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_698_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=8d4c19dc4acc83b831c6f81b70a02341&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Dr Paul Lewin, Dr Paul Chappell, Dr Jane Burridge" title="Dr Paul Lewin, Dr Paul Chappell, Dr Jane Burridge (Copyright: ECS)" border="0" width="120" height="85" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050318085617/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/698">Research tackles sensory-motor learning in rehabilitation</a></h3><p>One of the greatest challenges facing sensory-motor learning in rehabilitation is being tackled by researchers at the School of Electronics and Computer Science working with the University's School of Health Professions and Rehabilitation Sciences. Their research, beginning next month, will be the first of its kind to develop and apply iterative learning control techniques to re-learning movement.</p></div><p class="clearBoth"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050318085617/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/">More News</a></p><br style="clear: both;" />
